---
import Callout from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/Callout.astro";
import CodeBlock from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/CodeBlock.astro";
import ContentSection from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/ContentSection.astro";
import FeatureList from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/FeatureList.astro";
import InlineCode from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/InlineCode.astro";
import PackageInfo from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/PackageInfo.astro";
import DocsPage from "../../layouts/DocsPage.astro";
import { href } from "../../lib/link";

export const prerender = true;
---

<DocsPage
	title="Getting Started"
	description="Install and set up swipe-bar, a zero-dependency React library for native swipe sidebars and bottom sheets."
>
	<ContentSection label="What is swipe-bar?">
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
			Mobile users expect swipe gestures. They swipe from the edge to
			reveal a navigation drawer, pull up a bottom sheet, dismiss a panel
			with a flick. Building this yourself means wrangling touch events,
			drag thresholds, transition timing, focus traps, and cross-direction
			locking. The result is always fragile and hard to maintain.
		</p>
		<p class="text-white/60 leading-relaxed">
			swipe-bar handles all of that. Wrap your content in a provider, drop
			in a sidebar component, and you get native-feeling swipe interactions
			with zero configuration. Left sidebars, right sidebars, bottom
			sheets, multi-instance panels. Everything works out of the box.
		</p>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Rationale">
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
			Most sidebar libraries solve the wrong problem. They give you a
			styled drawer with an open/close API and call it done. The hard part
			was never the open/close state. It's the gesture handling: detecting
			edge swipes vs. scroll, managing drag physics, preventing two
			sidebars from fighting each other, handling mid-anchor points on
			bottom sheets, trapping focus for accessibility, and making it all
			feel native rather than janky.
		</p>
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
			swipe-bar sits in the space between a CSS drawer and a full design
			system. It handles the interaction layer that's genuinely painful to
			get right, and stays out of the way for styling and state management.
			Your CSS. Your layout. Your logic. The library just makes the
			gestures work.
		</p>
		<FeatureList features={[
			{ highlight: "Zero dependencies", description: "just React. No animation libraries, no gesture systems, no CSS frameworks bundled in", color: "accent" },
			{ highlight: "Native touch gestures", description: "edge-swipe detection, drag tracking with activation thresholds, velocity-based commit/cancel. Works on touch and mouse", color: "blue" },
			{ highlight: "Cross-direction locking", description: "opening one sidebar locks the others. No accidental double-opens, no conflicting gestures", color: "green" },
			{ highlight: "Bottom sheets with mid-anchor", description: "swipe up to a mid-point, swipe again to fully open. Like iOS Maps. Multi-instance support with independent state for all directions (left, right, bottom)", color: "purple" },
			{ highlight: "Typed sidebar metadata", description: "attach a generic type map to the context hook. Each sidebar gets its own typed meta, validated at compile time", color: "yellow" },
			{ highlight: "Full accessibility", description: "focus trap, Escape to close, aria attributes, keyboard navigation. All automatic", color: "accent" },
		]} />
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Installation">
		<CodeBlock
			code="npm install @luciodale/swipe-bar"
			language="bash"
			filename="terminal"
		/>
		<PackageInfo
			packageName="@luciodale/swipe-bar"
			githubRepo="luciodale/swipe-bar"
		/>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Quick Start">
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
			Three steps: wrap your app in the provider, add a sidebar component,
			done. The sidebar appears when the user swipes from the edge, or when
			you open it programmatically.
		</p>
		<CodeBlock
			code={`import { SwipeBarProvider, SwipeBarLeft } from "@luciodale/swipe-bar";

function App() {
  return (
    <SwipeBarProvider>
      <SwipeBarLeft className="bg-gray-900 text-white">
        <nav>
          <a href="/dashboard">Dashboard</a>
          <a href="/settings">Settings</a>
        </nav>
      </SwipeBarLeft>

      <main>
        <h1>Your app content</h1>
      </main>
    </SwipeBarProvider>
  );
}`}
			language="tsx"
			filename="App.tsx"
		/>
		<p class="text-white/60 mt-4 leading-relaxed">
			That's the whole setup. The left sidebar responds to edge swipes on
			mobile (below 640px by default) and shows a toggle button. On
			desktop, the toggle button opens and closes the sidebar. Every prop
			has a sensible default.
		</p>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Adding More Sidebars">
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
			Add right sidebars and bottom sheets the same way. All three
			directions work inside the same provider with automatic
			cross-direction locking:
		</p>
		<CodeBlock
			code={`import {
  SwipeBarProvider,
  SwipeBarLeft,
  SwipeBarRight,
  SwipeBarBottom,
} from "@luciodale/swipe-bar";

function App() {
  return (
    <SwipeBarProvider>
      <SwipeBarLeft className="bg-gray-900 text-white">
        <nav>Navigation</nav>
      </SwipeBarLeft>

      <SwipeBarRight className="bg-gray-900 text-white">
        <div>Settings panel</div>
      </SwipeBarRight>

      <SwipeBarBottom sidebarHeightPx={400} isAbsolute className="bg-gray-900 text-white">
        <div>Bottom sheet content</div>
      </SwipeBarBottom>

      <main>
        <h1>Your app content</h1>
      </main>
    </SwipeBarProvider>
  );
}`}
			language="tsx"
			filename="App.tsx"
		/>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Programmatic Control">
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
			The <InlineCode>useSwipeBarContext</InlineCode> hook gives you full
			control. Open, close, read state, and attach metadata:
		</p>
		<CodeBlock
			code={`import { useSwipeBarContext } from "@luciodale/swipe-bar";

function Header() {
  const { openSidebar, closeSidebar, isLeftOpen } = useSwipeBarContext();

  return (
    <header>
      <button onClick={() => openSidebar("left")}>
        Menu
      </button>
      {isLeftOpen && <span>Sidebar is open</span>}
    </header>
  );
}`}
			language="tsx"
			filename="Header.tsx"
		/>
		<Callout type="tip" title="Context scope">
			<InlineCode>useSwipeBarContext</InlineCode> must be called inside a
			<InlineCode>SwipeBarProvider</InlineCode>. It throws if no provider
			is found.
		</Callout>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Next Steps">
		<ul class="space-y-2 text-white/60">
			<li>
				<a href={href("/docs/configuration")} class="text-accent hover:underline">Configuration</a>
				&#8212; all provider and sidebar props in detail
			</li>
			<li>
				<a href={href("/docs/bottom-sheets")} class="text-accent hover:underline">Bottom Sheets</a>
				&#8212; mid-anchor, multi-instance, programmatic-only panels
			</li>
			<li>
				<a href={href("/docs/sidebar-meta")} class="text-accent hover:underline">Sidebar Meta</a>
				&#8212; typed metadata for each sidebar
			</li>
			<li>
				<a href={href("/docs/api")} class="text-accent hover:underline">API Reference</a>
				&#8212; every component, hook, and type
			</li>
		</ul>
	</ContentSection>
</DocsPage>
